# Nmap Scripting Engine
NSE is basically Nmap saying:  
_“Port scanning is cool, but what if I also ran mini-exploits, brute-forced creds, fingerprinted malware, enumerated users, found CVEs, AND made you breakfast?”_

It uses **Lua scripts**, grouped into **14 categories**, each with its own vibe.

Here’s the breakdown — clean, quick, and memorable:

###  NSE Categories (translated into real-human English)

|Category|What it’s really doing|
|---|---|
|**auth**|Finds login creds or tests auth mechanisms.|
|**broadcast**|Discovers hosts via broadcast packets.|
|**brute**|Tries logins via brute force (don’t use on fragile things).|
|**default**|Runs when you use `-sC` or `-A` — “safe-ish basics.”|
|**discovery**|Enumerates services deeper than default scans.|
|**dos**|Tests DoS weaknesses — kinda spicy, rarely used.|
|**exploit**|Tries actual exploitation of known vulns.|
|**external**|Talks to third-party services/APIs.|
|**fuzzer**|Sends weird packets to see what breaks.|
|**intrusive**|Could crash stuff — use only if you accept chaos.|
|**malware**|Checks for malware fingerprints.|
|**safe**|The wholesome scripts — no harmful touches.|
|**version**|Helps identify service versions.|
|**vuln**|Checks for known CVEs and security issues.|

