# ⚙️ Aggressive Mode (-A):

aka **“Nmap on Monster Energy.”**

`sudo nmap 10.129.2.28 -p 80 -A`

What you instantly get:

- Service versions (`-sV`)
    
- OS detection (`-O`)
    
- Default scripts (`-sC`)
    
- Traceroute
    
- Webserver headers
    
- Web app frameworks (WordPress detected!)
    
- Page title
    
- Sometimes CVE-relevant metadata
    

It’s loud. It’s fast. It’s borderline rude.  
But damn, it’s thorough.

---

#  Vuln Scanning with NSE

This is where you become the threat.

`sudo nmap 10.129.2.28 -p 80 -sV --script vuln`

This will:

- enumerate WordPress paths
    
- gather version numbers
    
- detect outdated files
    
- pull usernames
    
- check CVEs via `vulners`
    
- run light XSS checks
    
- find misconfigurations
    
- reveal interesting files
    

Actual example output you saw:

- WordPress 5.3.4
    
- Multiple legacy WP assets (v2.2 → v2.7 version drift)
    
- Username: `admin`
    
- Apache 2.4.29 CVEs: CVE-2019-0211, CVE-2018-1312, etc.
    

It’s basically doing free mini-pen-testing for you.

